### If/Else Statements

The `if` statement executes a block of code if a condition is true. The `else` block executes when the condition is false.

---

### Basic If

```cpp
if (condition) {
  // Code runs if condition is true
}
```

---

### If-Else

```cpp
int number = 10;

if (number % 2 == 0) {
  cout << "Even";
} else {
  cout << "Odd";
}
```

---

### Else If Chain

```cpp
int score = 75;

if (score >= 90) {
  cout << "A";
} else if (score >= 80) {
  cout << "B";
} else if (score >= 70) {
  cout << "C";
} else {
  cout << "F";
}
```

---

### Nested If

```cpp
if (x > 0) {
  if (x > 100) {
    cout << "Large positive";
  } else {
    cout << "Small positive";
  }
}
```

---

### Common Pitfalls

| Mistake | Wrong | Correct |
|---------|-------|---------|
| Assignment instead of comparison | `if (x = 5)` | `if (x == 5)` |
| Missing braces | `if (x > 0) cout << x; return x;` | `if (x > 0) { cout << x; return x; }` |
| Semicolon after if | `if (x > 5); { ... }` | `if (x > 5) { ... }` |

---

> **Key Point:** The `else` clause binds to the nearest `if`. Use braces `{}` to avoid dangling-else ambiguity.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  int temperature = 30;

  if (temperature > 35) {
    cout << "Hot day";
  } else if (temperature > 20) {
    cout << "Warm day";
  } else {
    cout << "Cool day";
  }
  return 0;
}
